{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650087"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:09:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:09:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18390"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18390"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11108"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77483"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11108"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62995"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11383"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25758"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26547"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77483"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the Orthopaedic clinic with chronic pain in her right ankle, which has been progressively worsening over the past year. She has a history of severe osteoarthritis in the affected joint. She has tried conservative management, including physiotherapy and analgesics, with limited relief. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The right ankle is swollen with limited range of motion and tenderness on palpation. X-rays show advanced degenerative changes in the ankle joint.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following surgical procedures is most appropriate for managing her condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arthroscopy","Osteotomy","Arthroplasty","Synovectomy","Arthrodesis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic ankle pain due to severe osteoarthritis, which has not responded to conservative treatment. The most appropriate surgical procedure in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Earthrodesis\u003C/strong\u003E, which involves fusing the joint to eliminate movement and relieve pain. This procedure is particularly suitable for joints like the ankle, where pain relief is prioritised over preserving range of motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E involves joint replacement and is more commonly used in larger joints like the hip or knee, where maintaining mobility is crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArthroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is a minimally invasive procedure used for diagnostic purposes or to treat certain joint conditions, but it is not suitable for severe osteoarthritis requiring joint fusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteotomy\u003C/strong\u003E involves cutting and realigning bones to relieve pressure on a joint, which may be considered in younger patients with joint deformities but is not appropriate for this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynovectomy\u003C/strong\u003E involves removing inflamed synovial tissue and is typically used for inflammatory joint conditions, not for advanced osteoarthritis requiring joint fusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Arthrodesis is a surgical procedure used to fuse a joint, eliminating movement to relieve pain.","Arthrodesis involves debriding cartilage, shaping bone surfaces, and using fixation to immobilise the joint until fusion occurs.","Arthrodesis is commonly performed on the ankle, wrist, foot, and spine."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379","Ombregt, L. (2013). A System of Orthopaedic Medicine-E-Book: A System of Orthopaedic Medicine-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62995"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18390"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62995"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T09:10:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T09:11:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11108"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77483"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"